A miner deposits collateral on an executor to "secure" the stability of it (I am putting up $100 to prove to renters that Im not going to remove the server)

Renters come through the lium.io website and their payments are shared between the miner and subnet owners (80/20)

A miner gets paid twice - one for providing the machine to the Celium Subnet (tracked on taostats/taomarketcap), two for rental income generated

The miners payout is staked to their hotkey in alpha so to convert it to Tao you would do btcli stake remove and you will see all of your stakes (1 for emmission, 1 for rental income)

A validator is paid based on how much stake they have and how well they do assigning weights to miners, as far as I know all the validators in the subnet just payout to their stakers. We agree with the intention behind the new rules — ensuring quality, uptime, and user satisfaction. At the same time, we believe that for the subnet to be healthy and scalable, rules must balance the interests of owners, providers, and renters alike. In addition to the ongoing discussion, we want to highlight how similar risks are handled across major cloud and GPU rental providers, using well-established SLA policies as reference.
Even top platforms like AWS, Azure, and Google Cloud only commit to 99%–99.9% uptime — meaning 10–100 minutes of allowed downtime per week. These are typically addressed via partial refunds or time-based credits, not full deposit forfeiture.
If just 2–3 downtime check trigger 100% slashing, the implied availability standard exceeds industry norms and creates excessive risk for providers.
Most platforms apply proportional penalties — for example, 1–10x the downtime duration — but none slashes hundreds of times that for 0.1%–0.5% unavailability.
Requiring 7–14 days of collateral also misaligns with how most GPU supply businesses operate. It may reduce available capacity and hurt the subnet's competitiveness in the long run.

From AWS azure, GCP 's SLA,  These show that requiring a 7-day deposit and enforcing 0-tolerance slashing for any downtime is not aligned with how the broader market manages service risk. As pointed out by others, hardware and network instability are inevitable to some extent. The key is how to quantify and manage this reasonably. Otherwise, with providers bearing nearly 100% of the risk, the current model risks discouraging participation — making it harder to deliver long-term quality service to end users.
